    en: "Perinton is one of the larger eastern-suburban towns in Monroe County. The town's Building and Codes Department is modern in its filing process — the GovWell online portal is one of the more polished municipal filing systems in the area — but the specific plumbing rules around licensing and homeowner work rely on phone confirmation.\n\nJurisdictional boundary. Perinton wraps around the Village of Fairport. A property with a Fairport, NY 14450 mailing address can sit inside village limits (under village Code Enforcement) or outside the village in the Town of Perinton (under Perinton's Building and Codes Department). The two offices do not share permit files. The Monroe County Real Property Portal confirms which office governs a specific address before the application is filed.\n\nOnline permit portal. Perinton uses the GovWell platform at app.govwell.com/perinton for permit applications. A plumber or homeowner creates an account, fills in the application online, uploads required attachments, and pays the fee through the portal. This is a more streamlined process than many surrounding towns still on paper applications.\n\nWhen a plumbing permit is required. Water heater replacement, new fixtures, sewer lateral work, water service line work, adding a bathroom, drain-waste-vent changes, and gas piping from the meter to an appliance all require a plumbing permit. The town follows the NY Uniform Fire Prevention and Building Code for technical standards.\n\n2025 fee schedule. The general residential building permit fee is $0.20 per square foot with a $50 minimum. Plumbing-specific fee structures (per-fixture versus flat fee) are not as clearly delineated in the public schedule. A call to [number being verified] confirms the current plumbing line-item fee for a specific project.\n\nPlumber licensing. Perinton does not have a separate plumber licensing chapter in the town code. Plumbers working in Perinton need current general liability insurance and workers' compensation coverage under Workers' Compensation Law 10. Whether the town accepts a Rochester Examining Board of Plumbers certificate in place of any local requirement is not explicitly published.\n\nHomeowner self-work. The town's public code does not clearly state whether a homeowner on an owner-occupied single-family home can pull a plumbing permit and do work personally. The Building Department confirms the current rule.\n\nInspection flow. After the work is complete, a town inspector performs the plumbing inspection against the Uniform Code. Inspections typically happen at rough-in (before walls are closed up) and at final.\n\nGas piping is plumbing. Gas piping from the meter to any appliance (furnace, water heater, range) is plumbing work in Perinton. An HVAC contractor replacing a furnace needs to coordinate with a qualified plumber for the gas line.\n\nContact hours. The Building and Codes Department is at 1350 Turk Hill Road. Hours are Monday through Friday from 9 AM to 5 PM. Email intake at building@perinton.org is also accepted for non-urgent questions.\n\nState protections. Wage theft protections (Labor Law 191 and 193), the Scaffold Law for elevated work (Labor Law 240 and 241(6)), mechanic's liens (Lien Law 3 and 10), and General Business Law 349 for deceptive home-improvement practices apply in Perinton as statewide. The statewide plumbing-residential-ny entry covers those layers."
